A bunch of things I wish I knew about ultra running before I started ultra running👇🏻

—You do not need to race at shorter distances prior to running or racing in your first ultra
—“Running toughness” is incredibly trainable
—Only 25% of ultra runners identify as she/her, but this number is increasing each year (let’s go, girls)
—Your mental and emotional health matter just as much as your physical health when it comes to running 30-100+ miles at a time
—The average ultra race pace is 13:16 and keeps getting slower due to so many folks joining the sport
—The average age for an ultra runner is 42 years old
—“Finishing” is a really great goal for your first ultra run/race
—You don’t have to train as much as you think you do finish an ultra run/race
—The human body is amazing at tolerating pain and discomfort once you trust it to do so
—The longer the run, the more women tend to outshine men… especially after 195mi (yay, pain tolerance)
—The ultra running community is super inclusive, welcoming, and wonderful (unlike the skiing community lolz)
—Long distance running is best when shared with friends

Less than 18 months ago, I was pretty nervous about leaning into ultra running because I thought I was too slow. I did it anyway. And I am so happy I stopped worrying about my speed and started focussing on having fun, enjoying the places I run, appreciating progress when I notice it, and learning how to settle into a new type of discomfort.🏃🏼‍♀️

Just goofin. Gear room goofin. I’ve been messing around with filming myself in my gear room so that I can start making you the types of videos you would expect one to make in a gear room… gear videos🤪🙃.

I hosted 6 international trips on 4 continents in 5 countries in 2022. It rips a hole in my mind that I got to take groups of people hiking/climbing in Patagonia, Nepal, Peru, Tanzania and New Zealand. While I’m incredibly grateful to get to travel for work and experience new places/things, it’s the friendships that I make on these trip that mean the most to me.

I hosted 62 travelers—54 women and 8 dudes—across the above mentioned countries. And I am so stoked to call them all friends now. Like my actual friends. I have matching tattoos with a bunch of them and I call/text/see many of them regularly.

When I reflect on my favorite memories from 2022, a lot them were on these trips. I had the absolute pleasure and honor of watching people get out of their comfort zones on rock, dirt and snow with complete strangers. I also got to watch dozens of friendships form and grow between my travelers. It was super magical stuff to get to be part of and worth every bit of the exhaustion I endured from hosting 6 international trips in 10 months.

Group trips with strangers hit different. They do something funny to you (in a good way) because in addition to opening yourself up to an entirely new country/culture, you’re opening yourself up to experiencing it all with a group of random people who might see it and feel it a little differently than you for a number of reasons. Which is so cool because it gives travel a whole new perspective. I got to see travel through other people’s lenses in 2022 and it made me appreciate it even more than I already did.
———
I have 2 group trips confirmed for 2023: Jordan in May and Mongolia in July. The Jordan trip is full with a waitlist but the Mongolia trip has a few spots left. Both of these trips lean more towards cultural exploration and are not physically demanding trips like my 2022 trips were. (There is also a beginner friendly Patagonia ski trip on the table, but I’m having a difficult time convincing enough people to fly to Patagonia to learn how to ski/snowboard with a group of strangers. Understandably.)

You can click the link in bio and swipe over to trips to learn more. Or just ask me all the questions!

On Monday, Dec 5th at 9am sharp I snagged 1 of 15 spots to compete in the Iron Crown at the @brokenarrowskyrace June 16-18, a few days before my 35th birthday. To quote my dear friend @kailankalina, “we are in it now”.

I will be racing 3 days in a row!!

On day one, I’ll be racing in the Iron Face Challenge which entails climbing the via ferrata as fast as possible then running back downhill, totaling 6.25-miles with 2,000’ vertical gain (fun).

On day two, I’ll be racing in the 46k which entails running 28.15-miles with 10,030’ of vertical gain (woof).

On day three, I’ll be racing in the 23k which entails running 14.25-miles with 5,030’ of vertical gain (fun).

So that’s 48.65-miles and 17,060’ of vertical gain in 3 days. Yeehaw🤠.

I’m so psyched. And a little nervous. Which is a good thing because it wouldn’t be as fun and rewarding it if didn’t intimidate/challenge me a bit. Excited to train for this thing the first half of 2023. And especially stoked to get to run with a few of my @sendfemme ladies that weekend.

LET’S GO!!!

**if you want to see more of my training for running, skiing and climbing, the best thing to do is follow me on Strava, as I only share a very small amount here these days due to being insanely busy**

I got gear shamed when I got back on skis in 2020, usually by men. I had *just* gotten back on skis as an adult an Ernie *just* had $20k worth of spine surgery (with more bills on the way). Not only did we not have the money to throw at fancy new gear at the time, I wasn’t even sure if skiing was going to stick for me.

When I started skiing again in 2020 I used my trekking poles, climbing helmet, and mountaineering shells for gear since I didn’t have ski-specific gear yet. I had one pair of skis/boots to use at both the resort and in the backcountry. It’s what I had at first and I made it work because I had to. And there isn’t anything wrong with this.

When I shared pictures/videos of myself skiing back in the beginning, I got a lot of “why are you wearing ____ at the resort?” type of comments about my clothes/gear. Lots of comments about using my trekking poles as ski poles. Plenty of comments about how I needed different/more skis. A few comments about the climbing helmet. Some comments about how I needed to buy insulated resort gear. So on yada yada. It was really annoying because it was 100% unsolicited and I simply didn’t give a fuck or ask for opinions on what to wear lol. I just wanted to ski.

Skiing is an amazing sport but it’s also expensive and gate-kept. You can sorta get around the expensive part but you can’t always avoid the dudes who think they own skiing because they’ve being doing it forever. If/when you run into these types of people, completely ignore them. They are to small and insignificant to be worth any of your energy.

I spent 2 decades thinking skiing was for rich white dudes which kept me off skis. Now I think skiing is for everyone and I hope that you get to try it one day if you want to and are able to. I also hope this helped you realize you can try/start new things without having all the perfect “stuff”. Now go get out there and have some fun!

✨Happy Holidays from The Harclerodes✨ Pulling over on the side of 395 to take pictures in matching sweaters this morning is the most festive thing we’ve ever done!

❤️Krissy, Ben, Ernie & Keaton (who can’t sit still for a picture)

I’m going to keep this short(ish), simple and honest.

I personally don’t feel the need to post a big philosophical end of year recap with all my “wins” of the year. All I have to say is that 2022 was really good to me, especially when I compare it to 2021 (one of the worst years of my life). Professionally and athletically, 2022 was stellar.

But my “success” came with a hefty price tag. Crushing my profesional and athletic careers cost me my TIME. Which means I didn’t have a lot of time to give family/friends in 2022 and this felt like total shit. I missed birthdays, holidays, and baby showers because I was training/working/traveling nonstop, selfishly pursuing my own stuff. While I’m incredibly proud of my accomplishments, I don’t want to be the friend or family member missing literally everything to be off in the mountains (or in front of my computer) all the time.

So my main goal for 2023 is simple… to still go big but without taking on so much so I can spend more quality time with family and friends. I can still show up for my loved ones while also being an accomplished athlete and businesswoman. I know I can and ima do it!

Happy new year, friends. Love you lots.
💜🥳🎉🪩🎊

(videos are some favorite memories and adventures from 2022 — 1: Denali, 2: NZ glacier tubs, 3: running across Grand Canyon and back, 4: Kilimanjaro, 5: Bear Creek Spire free solo, 6: climbing/hiking in Patagonia for three weeks, 7: the FKT we never submitted, 8: Annapurna Base Camp, 9: hiking in Peru, 10: lots of doing things on skis)

I’ve come pretty far on skis in a fairly short amount of time, largely because of others. I’ve been *very* fortunate to get to ski with people who have been skiing for an eternity, which has absolutely helped me improve over 3 seasons. I wouldn’t be where I am now if it weren’t for the support and guidance of experienced skiers.

The first person who comes to mind when I think about my progress is @ittybittywhittyyy. Her patience is truly unmatched. She’s been more patient with me on skis than I’ve been with myself on skis. I’m super good at being hard on myself and she’s super good at helping me knock that shit off.

The first time I attempted to ski off a true summit in the backcountry a little over 2 years ago, Whitney watched me GET OFF MY SKIS AND BOOT DOWN because I was scared. She supported me through the entire situation even though I was *incredibly* embarrassed. Then she came on my redemption ski when I went back to ski off the summit of that same peak.

Last season, she got me through a small panic attack when I realized I forgot my ski crampons as we were skinning up the steep part of a peak that was covered in rime ice. She got us to a safer spot to transition and we skied from there. Again, I was embarrassed, but she acted like it was no big deal and we still had all the fun that day once we found the good snow.

There are more examples of her heroic behavior, but I’m out of caption space.

I’ve come a REAL long way, Whit. Thanks for being such an inspiration as well as a big part of the process since literally day one. You’ve helped me stick with it so I could get to exactly where I am right now and I’m pretty dang stoked on what and where I am skiing in 4 weeks🥹💜⛷️.

If you don’t have one, get yourself a friend like @ittybittywhittyyy. She fell into my lap on accident almost 3 years ago and I’m so glad she did.
Got yeeted off a 1000’ cliff in Moab yesterday with some of my favorite people. Thanks for giving us a gift we’ll hold special forever @sylvanslacks and @sketchyandylewis.

I’ve been silently preparing to climb/ski a 6000m peak in Ecuador in a couple weeks, yeehaw🤠. Part of the preparation has been acclimatizing ahead of time so we don’t have to acclimatize in country. As much as I would LOVE to spend time in Ecuador, we don’t have the time to spend. In and out.

So we’ve been sleeping in a Hypoxico tent to simulate altitude. And I started using the mask attachment to train today (I’m very claustrophobic, so the mask has been a whole thing to work up to). For the next 3 weeks, I’ll be rowing/biking hooked up to the unit 2-3x a week for anywhere from 30-90 minutes each session. I’ll also be adding a little altitude each session. Yay technology. The goal is to feel as good as possible when we land in Quito, then it’s straight to Cayambe for a warm up ski before we attempt Chimborazo.

If you are interested in the altitude training, I’ll keep sharing the progress these next few weeks! If you think I’m unwell/insane, I’ll go ahead and keep this shit to myself🤪.

I took the 3-day AIARE level 2 course over the weekend to learn more about decision making while traveling in more complicated/complex backcountry terrain on my skis. As I’ve gotten more confident on sticks, my ski mountaineering goals have gotten loftier (imagine that🤪). And said goals require a decent amount of education when it comes to things like assessing avalanche hazard and snowpack.

If you’ve been around a while, you know how I feel about outdoor safety education: I believe it’s very important. Especially once you start dabbling in things that could result in an avalanche burial or a crevasse fall—both of which are often fatal. If you can’t afford courses, you can apply for scholarships to try to get them paid for. (Friendly reminder that there is a MASSIVE difference between actually not being able to afford something and not wanting to pay for something because it means sacrificing something else). Education can be expensive to obtain, but it is truly priceless once you possess and apply it.

I personally feel that we need to do our due diligence when it comes to keeping ourselves AND each other safe in the mountains. In order to be a solid teammate to my climbing/skiing partners, it’s my duty to learn as much as possible so that I’m an ASSET to a team and not a LIABILITY.

Thanks to @alpenglowexpeditions for running a great program in the Tahoe area. Thanks to @richmeyeralpineguide for being an absolutely incredible instructor. Thanks to pitmaster @peeeeeeeeeeeeeat for teaching us how to dig, observe, and record. And thanks to Ben, Frits, Lenny, John, Terry, Mike, and Greyson for appointing me—the only chick at the course—as tour leader🥰. In addition to being very educational, the course was FUN and I’m stoked I got to spend the weekend learning with a swell group of fellas.

ECUADOR SKI MOUNTAINEERING GEAR LIST👇🏻

I’m headed down to Ecuador with Ben on Wednesday for 8 days to attempt to climb/ski two objectives—Cayambe 5790m/18,996ft and Chimbo 6263m/20,594ft. We’ve been preparing for this trip for *months* and it’s all finally coming together. STOKED to get to climb/ski on the equator with my best friend and also stoked to sleep in huts instead of a tent on this trip (old ppl neck and back probs lol).

This list is my technical gear and does not include what I’m wearing on my body, head, hands, and feet to protect myself from cold temps, precip, and the sun. I can make a separate post about clothing and layers if you’re interested in all that.

Pack - Hyperlite Mountain Gear Headwall (55L)
Ice Axe - Grivel Ghost
Crampons - Grivel Skimatic 2.0
Harness - Petzl Altitude 
Helmet - Petzl Meteor
Headlamp - Petzl Swift
Ski Boots - Dynafit Radical Pro
Skis - Black Crows Navis Freebirds
Bindings - Moment ATK Voyagers
Skins - Black Crows Pilus
Poles - Black Crows Trios
Ski Crampons - Dynafit
Avy Gear - Mammut Barryvox S, shovel, probe
Crevasse Rescue Gear
Gear Repair Kit
Sleeping Bag - Mountain Hardwear Phantom 0
WP Stuff Sacks - Hyperlite Mountain Gear Pods

I used just about all of the above on Denali (and others) and I feel pretty dialed. My skis/bindings are a lil heavy for ski mountaineering, but I *love* them. I also do my squats, so heavy touring skis ain’t no thang🙃.

Let me know if you have gear questions!! Or any questions at all about the trip😘.

On Thursday Feb 16th @ 6:05am local time, I stood on the Veintimilla summit of Chimborazo (6230m/20,440ft) after a steep slog up snow, ice, and rock with Ben and Gaspar.

✨Neat fact: Chimborazo—the tallest mountain in Ecuador—is the closest one can stand to space on planet earth. Although lower in altitude, it technically rises about a mile higher than Everest due to earth not being a perfect sphere and Ecuador being on the equator bulge.✨

We came to Ecuador to ski but conditions didn’t allow for much skiing, as all the good snow melted before we arrived. And that’s ok. Because I had the best time with my best friend.

I climbed the tallest mountain in the country.
I skied from 5060m/16,600ft on Cayambe.
I fell even more in love with Ben.
I fell in love with Ecuador.
I fell in love with a dog.
I made friends.
I laughed.
I cried.

Thank you to our hero, @gaspar.navarrete.gangotena. We would not have kept pushing beyond 19,500’ if it weren’t for his encouragement to dig deep to embrace the high altitude suck. Chimbo was a slightly harder than anticipated and it spanked us a little bit, but Gaspar kept assuring us we were making it up.

Thank you to @alpenglowexpeditions for planning this expedition for/with us and handling logistics. International climbing/skiing trips of this level are still very new to us and I appreciate everything Alpenglow does to help climbers and skiers do cool things in cool places.

I can’t wait to go back one day, earlier in the season, to ski all the things. I’ve been to nearly 50 countries and Ecuador is absolutely in my top 5 for so many reasons!!

My heart is FULL💗

I skied naked with hundreds of other women/folks at @boottanfest yesterday. It was a beautiful, magical and empowering experience to participate in. I will *never* forget shredding completely nude in an act of “Full Frontal Freedom” on a Tuesday afternoon with hundreds of other skiers and riders, as I’ve truly never experienced anything quite like it.

This event is not only the world’s largest naked ski lap, but it’s also the largest backcountry ski/snowboard festival on the planet for women and gender minorities. It’s a safe place where we can be at peace with our bodies and experience the feeling of collective freedom. This event is important. Women and genderqueer people need a backcountry ski event all to ourselves, especially one like this. I highly suggest attending in the future if you are able to get to @bluebirdbackcountry in March!!

Skiing, nudity, tacos, music, and supporting women are most of my favorite things. It’s beyond perfect that @boottanfest brings all these things together in one place for us to connect with each other. I got to see old friends and make new ones against the beautiful backdrop of empowerment. So stoked.
❄️⛷️👯‍♀️🍑🤙🏂🌮🎶☀️

After running R3 on Oct 14th I gave myself a 4 month break from running (it was meant to be a 2-3 month break, but you know it goes🤷🏼‍♀️). I started running again 8 weeks ago and I’m super stoked on how it’s going. I thought progress would be a bit slower than this, but here we are!

Week 1: 10.13 miles / 135’ vert / 1h 37m
Week 2: 13.97 miles / 617’ vert / 2h 25m
Week 3: 17.61 miles / 2,762’ vert / 3h 26m
Week 4: 26.78 miles / 3,996’ vert / 5h 4m
Week 5: 34.20 miles / 4,859’ vert / 6h 19m
Week 6: 41.21 miles / 6,204’ vert / 7h 25m
Week 7: 32.92 miles / 4,944’ vert / 6h 23m
Week 8: 41.62 miles / 7,425’ vert / 7h 38m

I’m incredibly grateful for how my body is handling this running volume after months off. Apparently all the backcountry skiing from our bountiful Tahoe winter has carried over into spring trail running quite nicely🤝🏻. But I still have a lot of work to do these next few months.

Last year, I did the absolute bare minimum with my running training. This year, the bare minimum is simply not an option if I want to achieve what I’ve set out to achieve the first week of July with coach and suffer bestie @chelseamyntti. Excited to see where the next 8 weeks (and beyond) take me🏃‍♀️.

Photos: all the silly lil pics I took of myself post run last week💁🏼‍♀️ + Strava data (because we all know how much I love data🤪)
1️⃣ post long run + mileage/vert/time progress
2️⃣ post workout run + fitness gains from the last 2-4 months 🤯
3️⃣ post recovery run + miles per run from the last 6 weeks
4️⃣ post recovery run + total runs/miles/time/vert from the last 8 weeks
5️⃣ mid recovery run, no training data

I’ll update you on running progress every couple weeks whether you care or not!!😘 #krissyruns

My mental health hasn’t been the best the last few months. Anxiety and depression are things I’ve dealt with since I was a teenager so while I do feel like I’ve gotten better at riding their rides as I’ve grown older/wiser, they still aren’t fun rides to be on.

Many areas of my life are going great. So I’ve been pretending like everything is ok in an effort to not seem ungrateful for how lovely my life is. But mental illness doesn’t care how fit I am or how hard I work or how great my relationships are. It’s a sneaky motherfucker and it makes a person feel lonely and burdensome. When I’m in a funk, my brain tells me things that aren’t true and sometimes it takes me a while to realize they are lies before I can come out of it!

So I started doing things that I know make me feel better. I’m making better nutrition choices, I’m cooking more, I cleaned my house up, I’ve been on social media less, I’ve been going outside lots, I’ve been trying to not work 7 days a week, I’m remembering to take my medication, and I got a yucky/toxic/predatory person out of my life.

So that’s why I have been quiet on here. And it feels good to let you know what’s going on with me instead of pretending and/or not showing up. Thanks for sticking with me!! I started feeling a little better this week, so maybe you’ll be seeing more of me soon🤗.

I’m 11 weeks back into running after 4 months off and the last 3 weeks were my best weeks of running EVER, like in my whole life.

Week 9: 41.98 miles / 7,608’ vert / 7h 25m
Week 10: 48.03 miles / 7,687’ vert / 9h
Week 11: 52.47 miles / 7,100’ vert / 9h 20m
(weeks 1-8 are a few posts back)

Food and sleep are the reasons I’m able to handle this running volume right now. Even though I’ve been in a mental funk, I’ve been able to get 3100-3800 calories in most days and get 9 hours of sleep in most nights.

I’m off to Jordan🇯🇴 on Friday to host a trip, so I’m only getting 3 days of training in this week before 2 days of travel this weekend. While in Jordan I’ll do my best to get daily 45-60min morning runs in to maintain fitness while I’m out of my training routine until the 20th (I better be running 6min miles below sea level 🤣 jkjk).

To answer questions I’ve been getting in my DMs… yes I’m still lifting and yes I’m still skiing. I’m lifting 2x/week and skiing 1-2x/week. I’m not rock climbing at the moment because my right hand has been injured for over 2 months and I have a few digits out of commission.

Ok that’s all I got, thank for reading/caring about my running 🤗 as running is the glue that is holding me together right now😭.

I almost didn’t make it to Jordan. The day I left, everything that possibly could go wrong did go wrong. I almost threw in the towel at the Phoenix airport and bailed on the whole trip because it wasn’t looking like I was getting on a new flight anytime soon.

But I stuck it out, got my ass on a plane somehow, and arrived to Jordan a day late. (I think there’s a popular saying about late being better than never or something like that🤪).

I didn’t have my bag the first 5 days I was in Jordan. While this was a bit stressful and frustrating, it reminded me what matters most on these that trips I lead. It taught me that I don’t need very much at all to have a damn good time.

What I do need to have a damn good time is damn good people. And I had 19 of them with me for 8 days, ripping around Jordan on an adventure.

Alanna, Lynn, Steph, Alex, Carla, Christina, Alyssa, JoJo, Rosie, Lindsey, Mae, Hope, Kelly, Karen, Carolina, Nikki, Heidi, Marc and Mark… I love y’all so much. Thank you for trusting me and Mohammed in Jordan. I’ll never forget that Wadi Rum jeep rip for as long as I live.

I’m so grateful that I got to experience this place with these folks. I didn’t realize how badly I needed some “Desert Power” (where my Dune stans at?).

The trip highlights are going up in my stories later today. Is Jordan on your bucket list? If not, maybe I can get you to add it 😘 watch my stories (or the highlight if you’re seeing this a few days late).

I celebrated 10 years in recovery for drug addiction & alcoholism yesterday. In the best way I know how—a 12 hour day in the mountains, climbing/skiing/running 10,000 vertical feet with some of my favorite people.

We planned to start hiking at 5am. But when my alarm went off at 4:15, Ben declared it “way too early”. Given it was also his birthday yesterday, I said “I’ll tell the girls to sleep another hour”. Then we didn’t start till 7am… because, well, this is how we are🤣.

We hiked up on dirt for 1k feet before we got on snow & started skinning up up up. The weather forecasted was comically incorrect—it was unexpectedly hot+sunny. One of the homies has been having heat issues, so we set up the mid for her after 3k feet of skinning. Then another started having heat issues soon after. I thought the day might be done at 5k feet out of my concern for everyone being in the sun+heat.

But the crew stuck it out for me, even tho they were hot. They took turns lapping to/from the mid with me so that I could keep crushing my 10k vert goal. Even though I was confident being alone on the terrain, I only did half of a lap solo because they kept taking turns going back up with me🥹.

By the time I hit 8.5k feet, the team was over being in ski boots. We skied out & hiked back down to the trailhead, knowing I still had 1.5k feet left to reach my goal. So Chels & Whit offered to run the rest with me on dirt😭. We dropped our packs on the side of the trail, ditched our ski clothes & ran 5.25mi w/ 1.5k feet vert in our base layers. The final 700’ was mental AF so I let myself cry about it for about 90sec, then finished strong.

Big. Fucking. Day. For so many reasons. It was a good reminder that while I am fully capable of doing hard things alone… doing hard things is best when shared with others who get you.

Click the link in my bio to donate to @reps4recovery in honor of me hitting 10 years. Or text “KRISSY10” to 44321.
THANK YOU, LOVE YOU, GO ME.

Happy belated birthday to my BFF, my adventure buddy, my dog daddy: @benharclerode. You are the glue that holds me together on my bad days and I’m immensely grateful for everything you’ve done for me over the last 7 years—especially emotionally. Thanks for letting me make your birthday about me on Sunday and always supporting my biggest goals and objectives. I like you (most of the time lol) and I love you.

📸 @chelseamealo

When I first shared that I was going to attemp a 10k day in the mountains mostly on touring skis, a few people (men lol) felt the need to be condescending by letting me know what a big day this is. Implying I maybe wouldn’t be able to do it… simply because they hadn’t done it🙃.

I knew what a big day this is.
I knew I might not be able to do it.
That was the point.
I did it anyway.

Here’s the thing. The harder something is to achieve, the higher the reward is if you achieve it. These objectives/experiences do come at a cost—they are incredibly mentally/physically demanding, they require planning and problem solving, etc. But the return on the investment is responsible for more personal growth than I could ever possibly convey into words for you.

Doing hard shit is my favorite and I’m so glad I’ve never let a man tell me I can’t do something hard outside.

I had a blast running at the @brokenarrowskyrace over the weekend! Race recap👇🏻

I’m supposed to be in Boulder right now, running an ultra + rock climbing with friends. Instead, I’m at home working in my backyard. In ~the boot~.

I’d say my biggest weakness as a runner is not always knowing when to dial it back and slow the f down, especially during what are meant to be easy runs. I know there's a time and a place to push myself, but I seem to occasionally have poor judgment on the days I’m feeling really good. And I listen to my body beyond the point of reason, even though I know better.

I got a little cocky on what was meant to be an easy run on Wednesday. I was running downhill… faster than I’ve ever ran on trail… on a day I felt my best… and put a little too much faith in my body despite the voice in the back of my head saying “yo maybe slow down”. I rolled my ankle *very* badly running downhill at a PR pace.

It was twice its normal size within 20 seconds, I didn't have service, I didn’t have my inReach on me, and I was 3.25mi from my car at the trailhead. After I did a usability test (yay being a WFR), I determined it wasn’t broken and that I could walk out on my own. So I did!

I honestly thought it was going to be fine when I woke up on Thursday and that I’d be able to run by today. Then it started to bruise a bit on Friday. By Saturday morning I knew that I’m probably not running or climbing for 3ish weeks😭.

The swelling has gone down, the bruising is already better, it’s weight bearing, I’m not in pain, and I still have 95% ROM. I haven’t gotten an MRI, as I’m not sure if it’s necessary yet. But I’m definitely not going to mess with running on it until I’m confident it’s safe to.

So here I am and now I wait.
Bummed but staying positive since this isn’t a big deal in the grand scheme of things and I don’t think I’m seriously injured.
I will put pictures and videos of it in my story for all you sickos.
🫶🏻😘

Perhaps a semi-unpopular opinion… I love trail running but strongly dislike racing & competing in it.

Unfortunately, I’ve put quite a bit of unnecessary pressure on myself to race this year in an effort to legitimize myself as an ultrarunner. To who? I’m not sure.

Before I explain, I would like to say that the trail racing community as a whole is incredibly welcoming & encouraging. My dislike of racing has everything to do with who I am as a person & nothing to do with the community.

After I did a few unsupported & self-supported ultra distances in 2020/2021 (because what the hell else did we have to do then), the internet did what the internet does & made me feel like I need to race in order to “validate” myself as an ultrarunner. So many people asked me about racing, it felt like I had to. After running R3, even more people started telling me that I “had to” start racing soon.

I didn’t start long distance trail running to race or compete. I started to get fitter for mountain climbing then accidentally & unexpectedly fell in love with it. Ten months ago, racing felt like the next logical step. Now, I’m not so sure it’s for me & I think it does more mental harm than good (even when I podium for fuck’s sake lol).

So I’m racing in an ultra in September to give it another chance just to be sure. After that, I think I’m returning to running far through the mountains with a friend or two, carrying everything I need on my back.

Everything that has happened in my life the last 35 years has led me to this place of being able to handle full days of physical & mental suffering in the mountains with very little external support, if any. So it’s important I keep leaning into this for the right reasons rather than lean into racing for the wrong ones.

Plus, I’ll always be built for distance & not for speed😝

TLDR — don’t let anyone pressure you into doing things you aren’t super stoked on & stay true to yourself & your life mission✨

It’s National Recovery Month!! I started my path to recovery from drug and alcohol addiction and abuse in May of 2013 with a barbell and not much else at the time. Quitting substances allowed me to open a gym in 2015, then I used that gym to give people like me free access to weights to help them stay sober.

This little act of kindness accelerated into a 501c3 nonprofit organization known as @reps4recovery by 2018 (thanks to the army of people who helped me) and has since turned into a thriving community of people in recovery all over Reno in multiple gyms.

In honor of National Recovery Month, @reps4recovery is running its biggest fundraiser of the year from September 1-30. The program is thriving, but after a low donation year R4R needs financial help in order to *keep* thriving. If you swipe, you’ll see everything R4R currently offers as well as how much it costs to run the program.

I’m the team captain of “Runner’s High”. Our team fundraising goal is $10,000 of the $25,000 total R4R is trying to raise. I’m personally trying to raise $5,000 of this. Currently, the fundraiser total is $9,610, my team’s total is $4,285, and my total is $1,590. Which is an incredible start 9 days into the month.

Every cent counts right now (cliche, but true). There is no such thing as a “small donation” in the nonprofit world and $5 can often feel like $500. Please help if you can.

I always tell people that the two hardest things I have ever done in my life are 1) kicking hard drugs for good and 2) nonprofit work. These two things have truly made climbing 6000m peaks and running 50mi unsupported–things I do to stay on my path of recovery–feel like a walk in the park haha.

This nonprofit as well as the life you see me live are both a byproduct of me choosing recovery over substances on May 28, 2013. If I can do it, fucking anyone can. I believe this to be true with every ounce of my being and I believe in everyone who chooses recovery. This month and always.

Recovery is hard and messy and beautiful. Let’s celebrate and destigmatize it in September. Click the link in my bio to help R4R out this month.

On November 14th my breast implants are *finally* not going to be in my body anymore. As many of you know, I’ve been waiting years for explant surgery to happen. It’s finally officially on the calendar😊.

I’ve had my implants for nearly 11 years. I got them when I was 24 years old because I thought I needed them to be sexy. I do not need them to be sexy, attractive, confident, etc. and it makes me sad that I was once in a place where I thought I did.

I’m getting them out for 3 main reasons

1– The right one hurts. It’s laterally displaced and falls into my armpit when I lay on my back which is very uncomfortable. It also hurts on my long runs and bigger objectives. Additionally, I live with autoimmune + mental illnesses and I don’t think breast implants are in the best interest of my health.

2– I want to feel better (and more athletic) when I run and climb, two things that are very important to my mental and physical health. My implants are too big for my size and it can make certain activities difficult and/or painful.

3– I have been objectified and sexualized by men since the day I got them, as well as taken less serious as an athlete and entrepreneur by men for having them. I know all of this is a problem with men and not a problem with me, but it still makes me angry🙃.

Surgery info👇🏻
•Bilateral capsulectomy with explantation (removal of both implants and the capsular contracture scar tissue around them)
•My implants are under the muscle
•No lift necessary due to anatomy, age, health
•Dr. Virden is predicting small b cups after
•Estimated surgery time is 1.5 hours
•I can resume training after 2-3 weeks🤯
•I can ski after 1 week (if there’s snow🤞🏻)
•Recovery shouldn’t be too painful or difficult

I AM SO EXCITED AND SO HAPPY THAT THIS IS FINALLY HAPPENING🥳🥰

Immediately upon finishing running R3 last October, I said loudly to everyone within earshot—“50 miles is my cap for a run, I will never run more than 50ish miles at once”. And at the time, I thought I meant it.

Well there’s this insanely cliche, cheesy, and popular saying, perhaps you’ve heard it: “never say never”. I don’t know about you, but I’ve personally said “I’ll never” plenty of times in my life only to end up doing the exact thing I said I would never do. It happens.

I’m running 63 miles—something I said I would never do—in a less than 6 weeks from now.

My original plan was to find a 50mi race (since November is usually tricky for Eastern Sierra mountain objectives) within driving distance right before surgery. My 50mi race option that weekend is Run the Rock in Smith Rock which is a marathon lollipop loop, twice. Yuck haha.

My only other option is the Red Rock Canyon 100k, *exactly* where Ben will serendipitously be finishing up the AMGA Rock Guide course two days before the race. I took this as a sign to choose the 63mi distance (we love easier logistics), even if the miles intimidate me a lil bit.

I think I can do this and I think I might even be able to do it kinda well after all the work I’ve put in this year. Even if I don’t end up doing it particularly well, I’m pumped to keep training hard this month, pumped to do my friggin best on race day, and pumped see what happens in a new (for me) distance.

Yeehaw, let’s go 🤠 (because once this shit is done and I’m recovered from surgery, IT IS TIME TO SKI BABY and ski is life)

How much, what, and when I eat while consistently trail running 50 mile weeks🏃🏼‍♀️

The most important thing to mention is that calories are critical–especially at high training volumes–in order to both perform and recover. If you can’t recover from training, you can’t stay consistent with training, then you stop making progress because you’re stuck in a hole. If you ever think or feel that you are “overtraining”, you are probably actually under-recovering. You must eat (and sleep, but that’s a post for another day).

The second most important thing to mention is that I eat 100% for performance, longevity as an athlete as I get older, and overall health/wellness. I do not eat for aesthetics, leanness, or fat loss and haven’t for almost 8 years. Like many of you, I struggle with body image at times. One of the best things I have ever done for my relationship with my body is stopping intentionally trying to lose weight/fat about 8 years ago. You don’t need to get leaner to improve in sport. You need to train, eat, and recover smarter and better to improve in sport. I will die on this hill.

I’m exactly equal parts excited and scared for this upcoming surgery. Excited to feel better (I’ve been waiting years for this) but scared of the recovery process (patience isn’t my thing).

My *best case* scenario is that I’m resort skiing after 7-10 days, bc skiing + running after 2-3 weeks, and lifting + climbing after 4-5 weeks. To absolutely nobody’s surprise, I got really attached to these best case numbers at first and mapped out a sick training month for December. But the more I looked at the running and skiing volume I was expecting of myself so soon after surgery, the more I started to realize I was being a bit ridiculous. While it’s fun to assume that I’ll experience a “best case scenario” recovery, this is purely speculation and I have no way of knowing how long it will take.

So last week I let go of any and all expectations when it comes to training in Nov/Dec. I deleted the note with my plan and reminded myself that I can’t start training again until my body is healthy and recovered enough to. I’ll need to take as much time off from running and skiing as necessary and that’s that. Maybe it’ll be 2-3 weeks, maybe it’ll be 4-5 weeks.

My right implant has been in quite a bit of pain when I run the last 2 months. I still to have to run a 100k in about a week, but it’s really wonderful to know that this 62mi race will be the last time I run with a displaced 550cc silicone bag barely still attached to my chest. Woohoo!

I ran my first 100k on Saturday in the challenging (for me) desert terrain of Red Rock Canyon, a stark departure from my usual mountain running comfort zone. The unfamiliar landscape presented unexpected challenges and discomfort that had me contemplating dropping more frequently than I’d like to admit.

The first 16 miles were technical with sand, rock, and wash taking a toll on my hip flexors very early in the race. After kicking a cactus (ouch), a mild calf pull went down running in soft sand around mile 10 and started to get more uncomfortable by the hour. By mile 40, after being absolutely spanked by the sun for 3 hours, the discomfort had travelled up to the back of my knee and I was not stoked.

Despite wanting to drop at the 43 mile aid station, encouragement from @franc.sunseri convinced me to keep going. He set out with me as sunlight disappeared and paced me for 15 slow miles in the cold, dark desert. He kept me calm and moving through the discomfort as we alternated between hiking and jogging — he called it hogging.

And while the podium was far less important to me than finishing, I somehow managed to place🥈F despite all the drama from miles 40 to 64. The icing on the cake was 6 people I love immensely being there to watch me finish.

Staying on top of my nutrition and especially my hydration undoubtedly played a pivotal role in my ability to keep going. @benharclerode and @franc.sunseri crewing me at aid stations every 15 miles also gave me a magical mental boost, even if it meant lingering a bit longer than I should have.

This was a valuable experience that toughened me up. While I may not race in the 100k distance again soon, this test of endurance and time on feet was crucial for my ambitious non-race goals in 2024, solidifying my grit and paving the way for future objectives. Yeehaw.

Lastly, I can’t believe that was my last run with big fake boobs. YAY!

Howdy 👋🏻 I’m a little over one month post op from explant surgery! I haven’t been sharing much because I haven’t had much to share. Physically, I couldn’t have asked for a speedier recovery. Mentally and emotionally, however, it’s been quite the ride.

The day before surgery I thought perhaps running a 100k two days prior was a bit foolish and that my body might have a tough time recovering from the race and surgery at once. Thankfully it was a nonissue and I recovered quickly and well from both (yay food!).

Due to having *very* little breast tissue, not getting a lift, and only having scar tissue built up in one area of my chest, I didn’t need drains after surgery–which is a big reason why I recovered fast. I got the green light to start jogging at two weeks post op but chose to hold off a week for a few different reasons.

Following my surgeon’s guidance, I gradually resumed easy/light activity: walking and lower body lifting at one week post-op, skiing at two weeks, road running at three weeks, and trail running at four weeks. I was fully cleared on Thursday to resume training as normal at one month post op and I can start climbing and upper body lifting as soon as I feel ready to try!

I feel awesome. No more chest or back pain when I run on flat or downhill terrain, I can lay/sleep on my back without pain or discomfort, and even simple tasks like shaving my armpits are easier. Being free of 1100cc of silicone gel on my chest has not only brought physical relief but also an unexpected compliment—people saying my face looks a little younger.

I’m slowly working through the body image issues that have come with this surgery. But the more I move my body, the less I worry about what it looks like, because it feels so good to feel so good after being in pain for so long.

Here is what else I’ve been doing the last month: brought my garage gym back to life, got the @blackironnutrition / @blackirontraining new year challenge ready, lots of dogs, lots of puzzles, and started back squatting again for the first time in 6 months.

2023 — Terrible year for my mental health, phenomenal year for my training/fitness. 

The juxtaposition of feeling incredibly physically healthy, well, and fit while also feeling mentally/emotionally unwell was intense for me this year, but I’m grateful for the experience because I learned and grew from it. 2023 taught me so much about who and what deserves my love/energy and who and what does not. Stoked to run it back on my training in 2024 while also taking better care of my mind, heart, and soul.

Thank you for being patient with me in 2023 as I struggled to show up on here. And thank you to everyone who checked in with me with year. Happy New Year, buddies.
